# Navigation

@divider

@callout .info
The navigation file handles what pages appear in the navigation bar, how they are grouped and ordered.
@end callout

@row

@card
## Navigation File
@divider

The navigation bar is generated from the `navigation.mq` file in the root of your project. This file contains links to every page in your site. 

It automatically generates submenus based on the path of the linked pages. For example, if you link to `docs/configuration.mq`, Marque will create a "Docs" menu with a "Configuration" submenu.

@end card

@card

Here is a sample `navigation.mq` file:

@row

@card
```md
[Home](index.mq)

Start Here

[Quick Start](quickstart.mq)
[Create Website](create.mq)

Migration

[Migration](migration.mq)
    [From mdBook](migration/mdbook.mq)
    [From MkDocs](migration/mkdocs.mq)
```
@end card

@card
![Navigation Preview](nav_preview.png)
@end card

@end row

@callout .warn
The indentation in the `navigation.mq` file is not important, but for readability. Marque generates submenus based on the path of the linked pages. So, if you link to `docs/configuration.mq`, Marque will create a "Docs" menu with a "Configuration" submenu, regardless of the indentation in the `navigation.mq` file.

@end row

# Navigation
@divider

`navigation.mq` controls the menu structure for your site.

@callout .info
This is the primary filename for the navigation file.
For backwards compatibility, Marque still accepts `summary.mq` in older projects.
@end callout

## What it controls
@divider

@row
  @card .primary
    ## Order and labels
    @divider
    The links in `navigation.mq` decide which pages appear in navigation, what order they appear in, and which label each page uses in the menu.
  @end card

  @card .secondary
    ## Grouping and hierarchy
    @divider
    Plain text lines become section headings, and page nesting is derived from page paths such as `docs/configuration/frontmatter.mq`.
  @end card
@end row

@card
  ## Home page
  @divider
  The first linked page becomes the site's home route. In most projects that will still be `index.mq`.
@end card

## Basic example
@divider

@card
```navigation.mq
# Navigation

[Home](index.mq)

Start Here
[Quick Start](quickstart.mq)
[Create Website](create.mq)

Docs
[Docs](docs.mq)
[Configuration](docs/configuration.mq)
[Frontmatter](docs/configuration/frontmatter.mq)
[Layouts](docs/configuration/layouts.mq)
```
@end card

@row
  @card
    ## Link entries
    @divider
    Use markdown links to point at `.mq` pages. The label inside the link becomes the navigation label.

    ```txt
    [Quick Start](quickstart.mq)
    [Layouts](docs/configuration/layouts.mq)
    ```
  @end card

  @card
    ## Section headings
    @divider
    Plain text lines act as headings. They help structure the sidebar and provide visual separation between groups.

    ```txt
    Start Here
    Docs
    Migration
    ```
  @end card
@end row

## How nesting works
@divider

@card
Marque derives nesting from page paths, not from indentation alone.

If a page lives under another page's path, it can appear as a child in navigation:

```txt
[Configuration](docs/configuration.mq)
[Frontmatter](docs/configuration/frontmatter.mq)
[Layouts](docs/configuration/layouts.mq)
```
@end card

@callout .ok
This keeps the navigation file readable. You list the pages in the order you want, and Marque works out the path-based hierarchy.
@end callout

## Common mistakes
@divider

@row
  @card
    - adding a page under `pages/` and forgetting to add it to `navigation.mq`
    - changing a page slug and forgetting to update the matching navigation entry
    - assuming indentation alone controls nesting
  @end card

  @card
    - using `nav = ...` in frontmatter and expecting that to set navigation order
    - pointing at `.html` output files instead of `.mq` source pages
    - treating `navigation.mq` like a page inside `pages/`
  @end card
@end row

